===Etymology 1===
{{ja-kanjitab|こ|yomi=k|alt=児:uncommon,娘:female}}

{{IPAfont|⟨ko<sub>1</sub>⟩}} → *{{IPAchar|/kʷo/}} → {{IPAchar|/ko/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|-|sort=こ}},<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref> attested in the ''{{w|Kojiki}}'' (712 {{CE}}) and the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'' (''c.'' 759 {{CE}}), two of the oldest examples of written Japanese.

Cognate with {{m|ja|蚕|tr=ko||[[silkworm]]}} and possibly {{m|ja|小|tr=ko||[[little]]|pos=diminutive prefix}}.

Possibly cognate with {{cog|zkg|仇|tr=*gu|sort=こ}}, which appears in an ancient place name with an apparent meaning of {{m|en|child}}.<ref>{{cite-journal
|author=John R. Bentley
|title=The Search for the Language of Yamatai
|journal=Japanese Language and Literature
|year=2008
|volume=42
|issue=1
|page=17
|url=https://www.academia.edu/37594511/The_Search_for_the_Language_of_Yamatai
|passage=This etymology is indirectly supported by evidence from the Koguryo onomastic data: ‘child peak’ is preserved as 仇斯波衣, where 仇 *gu is ‘child’. Thus, the peninsular word is likely *ku, and a plural sufﬁx ''-ra'' was later attached. This may have been reinterpreted later as singular ‘child’, much as modern Japanese ''ko-domo'' ‘child-plural’ is used as a singular with ''ko-domo-tati'' ‘child-plural-plural’ as the plural.
}}</ref>

